article.description:
Dana Cherry made a layup with 6
seconds remaining to give No. 14 Arkansas a 62-60 win over
Mississippi on Sunday.
article.headline: Cherry makes winning layup with six seconds left
article.linkText: Cherry's late layup lifts Arkansas over Mississippi
article.story:
FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Mississippi coach Ron Aldy hated to
see his team lose, particularly after the way the Lady Rebels
played (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) Arkansas down to the last minute.
	   
"This was the kind of game we envisioned it to be,'' Aldy said
after his team lost to the Lady Razorbacks, 62-60, on Sunday. "It
was a shame that both teams played hard, both teams made big plays,
and it's one of those games ... to where you hate to see either
team lose.''

	   The Lady Rebels held the score at 60-59 before Arkansas' Dana
Cherry took the ball to the basket, giving the Lady Razorbacks
(18-5, 5-3 Southeastern Conference) the win with 6 seconds
remaining. Cherry led with 19 points.

	   "They don't respect her 3-point shot, so they always let her
have a little bit of cushion,'' Arkansas coach Gary Blair said of
the last play. "This time, there was so much cushion ... it scared
me. ... She did the right thing. Instead of taking the jumper, make
a train wreck happen and that's what she did.''

	   The pressure shot was similar to India Lewis' last-second
3-pointer at Alabama, when Arkansas won 59-58.

	   "We played a lot better today than we did against Alabama,''
Blair said. "That's how it is in the SEC -- teams hitting big shots
under pressure.''

	   Ruby Vaden, who had been in a shooting slump since Arkansas beat
then-No. 2 Louisiana State on Jan. 19, came off the bench to add 13
points, shooting 5-of-9 from the field and 3-of-4 from the line.

	   Vaden has started 16 of Arkansas' 23 contests this season but
didn't start against Mississippi because she wanted to be able to
focus on the game more.

	   "I think coming off the bench ... helped me see the game more
before you get out there and just rush into things,'' Vaden said.
"I got out there and focused on my shots more and put them in the
basket instead of over the basket.''

	   Carletta Brown scored 18 points for Ole Miss, and Amber Watts
added 16 for the Lady Rebels (12-10, 2-7).

	   Ole Miss opened the scoring but a Lewis 3-pointer from the top
of the key gave Arkansas the lead for most of the first half. The 3
by Lewis was her only bucket of the game.

	   The Lady Razorbacks led by as many as nine points, but several
trips to the free-throw line and back-to-back 3s by Brown and
Tywanna Inmon quickly closed the gap.

	   A pair of 3-pointers by Tia Watson gave Ole Miss a 35-29
halftime lead.

	   "When we went to our bench, we got out of sync,'' Blair said.
"All the sudden they hit open jumpers. ... If you give open
jumpers to a team that's struggling from the field like they have
been doing all year, then that's going to get their confidence.''

	   Arkansas finished the game shooting 39.3 percent from the field,
and Ole Miss shot 35.8.

	   The teams traded baskets early in the second half, but Arkansas
went on a 10-0 run and tied the game at 41.

	   Three minutes passed before either team scored. Vaden finally
hit a layup at 12:13 to give Arkansas the lead, but the teams
traded baskets and the score remained tied. Brown made an easy
layup midway through the second half to give Mississippi a 47-45
lead.

	   Rochelle Vaughn nailed a 3 to give Arkansas a 58-55 lead with
4:18 left to play. But free throws by Brown and Watts put the Lady
Rebels up 60-58 with just more than a minute to go.
